### Section 3: Remediation Recommendation

**Recommended Measure: Implement Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA / 2FA)**

**Effectiveness Analysis:**
To prevent future brute-force access attempts, it is highly recommended to enforce Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) for all administrative accounts.

Brute-force attacks rely entirely on exploiting weak, predictable, or default passwords by guessing combinations until one works. Even if an attacker successfully guesses or acquires a valid administrative password, MFA introduces a mandatory secondary layer of verification—such as a time-based one-time password (TOTP) from an authenticator app or a hardware security key. Because the external attacker lacks physical access to the administrator's secondary device, the authentication chain is broken, effectively neutralizing the utility of the guessed password and securing the administrative panel from unauthorized access.
